<font color="#FF0000">VETS AND NON-VETS A DIALOGUE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec 26 23:59:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
What a sad state we are in when 25 years after a war,<br>
we deteriorate to the level of this thread. Chill out<br>
and lets have a dialogue, not a spam session.<br><br>
As an active anti-war protester, I deeply and strongly<br>
disagree with calling vets baby killers. It was wrong<br>
then and is wrong now. <br><br>
I actively avoided going to Vietnam, and I am not <br>
ashamed to say that. I thought the war was wrong and<br>
made a decision that I would not participate in <br>
it. I also made the decision that I would do all I <br>
could to help others not participate in it. I fought<br>
hard, and long 8 years to help stop the war. <br><br>
I make a distiction between the soldiers who went and<br>
the leaders who knowingly led us into war for reasons<br>
that had nothing to do with freedom for Vietnam. <br><br>
It is true that poorer people (which includes a dispro-<br>
portionate ratio of non-white people) have less options<br>
available to them to avoid going to the war. It is also<br>
true that many poorer people chose to join the military<br>
because it was one of the very few options where they<br>
could get a job. <br><br>
It is also true that across the spectrum of America<br>
people enlisted for altruistic reasons. I do not think<br>
that what they did was good for the Vietnamese people, but<br>
I do believe that those who enlisted generally thought<br>
what they were doing was for the good of the Vietnamese<br>
people. I hold no ill will to those who faught. I hope<br>
that those who went can also see that the anti-war<br>
movement was not an anti-GI movement. I do hold ill will<br>
towards the leaders of the US who knew that what they<br>
were doing was not for freedom in VIetnam, but for<br>
the financial betterment of the richest people in<br>
America. LBJ, McNamara etc. were responsible for<br>
knowlingly causing the deaths of thousands of Vietnamese<br>
and Americans for the avarice of a few.
<p><code>-- jproujan@k12s.phast.umass.edu  (Jed Proujansky) </code><p>


